ce:section.ce:para:
The biomedical applications of DM-CDs require them good biocompatibility, so the cytotoxicity of DM-CDs to RAW264.7 cells (Fig. S8a) and HeLa cells (Fig. S8b) was determined by standard MTT assay. It could be seen that the viability of RAW264.7 cells and HeLa cells was more than 80% upon incubating with 0–500 μg mL−1 and 0–300 μg mL−1 of DM-CDs, respectively. This result implying DM-CDs hold great promise for monitoring intracellular ClO− and GSH. Hence, cell imaging experiments were conducted to further demonstrates the practical availability of DM-CDs. As expected, a significant fluorescence signal could be observed from the intracellular region of RAW264.7 cells or HeLa cells after incubated with DM-CDs (0.3 mg mL−1). The bright red fluorescence signal became weaker when the cells further incubated with exogenous ClO−, and then recovered to a certain extent by exogenous GSH (Fig. 5
                        ). The feasibility of DM-CDs in monitoring the fluctuation of endogenous ClO− in living macro-phage and HeLa cells was further studied. Lipopolysaccharide (LPS) and phorbol 12-myristate 13-acetate (PMA), which is the stimulator and the activator for generating ROS, respectively, were used to produce endogenous ClO−. A moderate decrease in fluorescence was observed after the cells stimulated with LPS/PMA and then recovered to a certain degree by exogenous GSH (Fig. 6
                        ). The fluorescence intensity of each picture shown in Figs. 5 and 6 are analyzed by using ImageJ according to the reference [65], and the results are shown in Fig. S9. The imaging processed was shown in Video S3 (HeLa cells) and S4 (RAW264.7 cells). These data indicate DM-CDs are suitable for detecting exogenous or endogenous ClO− and exogenous GSH in living cells.
